Also @pareksha , </> is a subset of <>, note the same literal opens and ends tag

The top level for filter_name, *filter_args in filters.items() already iterates over all the filters. This should be pretty straight forward and not requires this kind of looping.
dict_filters = {}

for filter_name, *filter_args in filters:
  filter_args = tuple(filter_args)
  dict_filters[filter_name] = filter_args
Why won't this work?

I changed filters from a list into a dict.
The new filters is
{'language': ['c', 'java'], 'can_fix': 'syntax', 'section_tags': 'save'}

